		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=109628&amp;sid=b3a8fc0cd9caebf6d632ee74f2afd565#109628"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Mar 15, 2005 7:02 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Class Re-Envisioning</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=109628&amp;sid=b3a8fc0cd9caebf6d632ee74f2afd565"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Of interest to me was a statement in general and the entire Enchanter section.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We will remove the hard coded aggro generated by poison based debuffs which will result in some DoTs and Tash generating less aggro than they currently do as well as more consistent aggro generation.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
As a level 66 Ornate/LDoN/Luclin geared enchanter, I never invested in the Spell Casting Subtlety (agro reduction) AA.  Primary reason, I saw part of my role as agro-management.  Pulling agro off a healer with a single, irresistible, fast cast spell was great and fun.  When we attempted Ring of Vulak, I used that and slow to rune-tank adds (though the flurries made me go splat).
<br />

<br />
So much for rune-tanking when mez/root/charm are not available/viable forms of crowd control.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We will add higher level upgrades to the Word of Morell spell line.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">.
<br />

<br />
I used WoM primarily for mez/recharm in combination with the mez mastery AA (extended WoM to 12 seconds).  Was also useful in close quarters crowd control (LDoN).  Biggest drawback in PoP zones was its small range (giant models could hit you melee and be outside its ae).  Would be useful if charm was still viable.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We plan to change the way mana drain works.  In the past the spell had diminishing effects on NPCs above level 53.  We will be removing that limitation so you can use Theft of Thought on higher level caster NPCs and we can introduce more powerful spells in that line, in the future.  However, we will also be changing drains so that they only return the mana the NPC has instead of always returning the full amount.  If an NPC only has 100 mana and your spell does a 400 drain, you will only get 100 mana.  This is a necessary change as most NPCs, including non-casters, are given small amounts of mana in order to power some innates.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Allow me to translate:  Mana Sieve is still useless.  Scryer's will likely be nerfed in OoW+ beyond.  No, you won't be able to gimp our mob's special attacks in GoD+ beyond.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We all know that the power of NPCs has climbed and the difficulty in charming NPCs has retreated.  This has led to an imbalance where you were able to charm NPCs that do far more damage than ever intended and with minimal risk.  This lead us to the unfortunate decision to make many NPC's uncharmable.  With OOW, we introduced a change to charm that allowed us to make most NPCs charmable again, but reduce their effectiveness and remove the gameplay imbalance.  We did this by reducing their stats while charmed.  This presented some new problems though, the largest of which is you like to haste and buff your pets to get the most out of them and when the charm breaks, you face a much more powerful NPC.  We have a plan to ensure charm’s usefulness and want to gather your opinion before putting it into motion.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Charm is dead in OoW+ beyond.  They know this because they really looked at how often the spells are used in those zones.  They have decided on a plan which they say will address this.  Feedback from the enchanter community is basically the same as it was in Sept 2004 with the charm nerf.
<br />

<br />
Like some others, I used charm because of the high risk = high reward.  Also, because as I leveled, there were fewer and fewer opporunities to mez as single pulling became preferable to in-camp crowd control.  Simply put, charm was the last reason I played an enchanter as a main, over a boxed buffbot/one-key macro slower.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">a.       We want charm to be an integral part of your gameplay.  You should be able to grab a charmed pet in most circumstances and use that to benefit your group.
<br />

<br />
b.      We will be looking at the stats NPCs use when charmed to ensure they are within the intended range.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If they thought the severe hit power reduction was way out of whack, they would've changed it earlier than this.  Currently, mobs that hit 800-1200 in OoW content hit for 200-260 when charmed.  Even doubling this is not enough to balance the risk of a charm break on first engaging a mob (when slowing is key to keep the tank/puller/healer alive).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">c.       We would like to add innate buff effects to enchanter charm spells.  While an NPC is under the effects of the charm, they will also be under the effect of spells similar to what you would use to buff your pet.  When charm breaks those effects will go away so you are only dealing with the NPC in its base state.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If they were seriously looking into adjusting the damage tables as they hint at above, this wouldn't be necessary.  Basically, they are going to prevent buffing charmed pets past any dps output that they will hard-code.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">d.      The change mentioned above would cause further imbalance in zones where NPCs don’t currently lower their stats when charmed, the changes that were made in Omens will need to be made across the rest of the game and this will be the way new charm works in all of Norrath.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is the most puzzling and disturbing statement.  The whole point in charming in HoH, Tactics, Tipt, and Vxed was you buffed your pet into a killing machine and stayed way the hell away from it while going about your business.  Beyond enchanter soloing and partnering (rule of 3 change circa 2003 prevented pet tanking in full groups - beyond the snarer and healer, others in Tipt / Vxed were along for the ride), there was usefulness of pets in certain raid events - notably RD (which I had the pleasure to both wipe to and defeat) and RZtW (which I never attempted).
<br />

<br />
Killing charm in pre-OoW zones will impact guilds in these 2 events in particular.  Some would say this would be offset by level 70 power and equipment.  If you're already level 70 will spells and gear from OoW and DoN, why the hell would you bother with this content anyhow?  It's probably a heck of a lot easier to find people / guild to gimp you into the Ele's for your Time flags if you really, really want to see that zone.
<br />

<br />
This is apparently the approved SoE method for smaller/younger guilds to gain access to the elementals.
<br />

<br />
Brenlo stated soloing would be addressed in a future discussion of class re-envisioning.  Effectively, this proposal prevents the casual enchanter from charm soloing level 8+.  In addition, the buff on the charmed mob (as an innate funtion of all charm spells), prevents "reverse charming" as a viable means of soloing in OoW+ beyond as it boringly exists today.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">e.       After charm changes for all zones, we can go back and open up the use of charm in areas where it was previously excluded due to balance problems making charm much more usable throughout the game world.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
SoE made a similar statement in this regard back after the OoW charm nerf.  The result?  Giant models previously charmable in BoT were flagged un-charmable (not sure if that was change post my retirement).  Zone revamps of Mistmore and Lavastorm included the new charm nerf, as does the DoN expansion.
<br />

<br />
Existing zones (especially those keyed zones in GoD expansion) did not see any changes to charm.  Everything there is still uncharmable.
<br />

<br />
Skepticism aside, charm is simple unviable in its current state in newer zones; small reward for high risk.  Who cares if they expand it to other areas?
<br />

<br />
I made a much more concise post over at <a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=7652" target="_blank" class="postlink"> TheRunes.net</a>.  To summarize:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Charm is dead.</span>
<br />

<br />
Logging back to WoW, no reason to re-activate accounts.
<br />

<br />
Nokei Orhaste, former chanter of HoA<br />
